# 🚢 Titanic Survival Analysis — EDA & Machine Learning

An exploratory data analysis and machine learning project to predict passenger survival on the Titanic.

---

## 📌 Project Overview

The Titanic dataset is one of the most iconic datasets in data science. This project performs in-depth Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) to uncover survival patterns, followed by building a Machine Learning model to predict passenger survival.

---

## 📁 Dataset

- **Name:** Titanic Dataset
- **Source:** [EDA_Titanic.csv)
- **Records:** 891 passengers
- **Features:** 12 columns including Pclass, Sex, Age, Fare, Embarked, SibSp, Parch, etc.
- **Target:** `Survived` (0 = No, 1 = Yes)

---

## 🔧 Libraries Used

| Library | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `pandas` | Data loading & manipulation |
| `numpy` | Numerical operations |
| `matplotlib` | Data visualization |
| `seaborn` | Statistical plots |
| `scikit-learn` | ML model & evaluation |

---

## 🚀 Project Workflow

1. **Load Data** — Titanic CSV
2. **Data Overview & Missing Values** — Shape, dtypes, null counts
3. **Data Cleaning** — Handle missing values, drop irrelevant columns
4. **Univariate Analysis** — Distribution of individual features
5. **Bivariate Analysis** — Survival vs each feature
6. **Multivariate Analysis** — Combined feature interactions
7. **Machine Learning Model** — Random Forest Classifier
8. **Feature Importance & Insights** — Key survival predictors

---

## 📊 Key Findings

- 🚺 **Females** had significantly higher survival (~74%) vs males (~19%)
- 🎩 **1st class** passengers survived more than 3rd class
- 👶 **Children** had better survival chances
- 👨‍👩‍👧 **Medium family sizes** (2–4) showed optimal survival patterns
- 💰 **Higher fare** correlated with higher survival probability

---

## 🔍 Feature Importance (Random Forest)

| Feature | Importance |
|---|---|
| **Sex (Gender)** | Highest |
| **Pclass** | High |
| **Fare** | High |
| **Title** (extracted from Name) | Moderate |
| **Age** | Moderate |
| **FamilySize** | Moderate |

